# The Core AI dead end (2026-07-15). A 4 GB float32 Stable Diffusion 1.5 export that works,
# kept on disk because it cost real time to make — but it is an artifact, not a foundation,
# and the direction was called off. See `coreai-export/README.md` and HISTORY 2026-07-15.
#
# Ignored rather than committed: 4 GB in git history follows every clone forever, and this
# is a model we decided not to use. The folder's README is ignored along with it — HISTORY.md
# is the durable record, not that file.
coreai-export/

# Mark's unpublished writing — drafts and notes he is NOT ready to make public
# (2026-07-18). Purged from history and force-pushed; kept on disk, ignored here so a
# stray `git add -A` can never put them back on GitHub. Git can't do "committed locally
# but never pushed" on a shared branch, so these live on disk, untracked, until Mark
# decides to publish (then remove the line). Other personal docs remain public by his
# choice — this list is only what he asked to pull back.
Thomas_Article_DRAFT.md
Second_Article_NOTES.md
Technical_Post_NOTES.md

# NOTE — a deliberate deviation from Posey's .gitignore, which excludes its test
# materials as "large files, not for version control":
#
#   `Test Materials/` IS committed here.
#
# Posey's corpus is a convenience; ours is a scientific instrument. Every
# characterization result in HISTORY.md refers to specific images by name. The corpus
# was fetched by searching Wikimedia Commons, and Commons search results CHANGE — a
# re-fetch would silently return different pictures, and every recorded finding would
# quietly stop corresponding to the thing it described. A corpus that drifts isn't a
# corpus. It's ~15 MB. That's a cheap price for results that stay true.
